Movie: The Randall Scandal: Love, Loathing, and Vanderpump

Review: This movie could’ve been a great movie had they explored and showed the viewers more about Nicholas and his struggles/background. There were a lot of uncomfortable scenes that detail and represent depression in the darkest forms, but I found it ironic that the movie focuses more on the parents (mostly the father), rather than the son. Why did Nicholas feel this way? What happened in the years between his childhood and teenage-hood. It’s not always so black and white —…

I remember wanting to watch this as a teenager … and I’m happy I finally did. While the movie is bombarded with tons of explicit shots (ass, tits, coke snorting, etc.) and may feel like a complete movie about partying, the film does take a serious approach to convey a couple themes, mainly: women empowerment, spiritual awakening, and overall consequences to actions in life. It’s a weird juxtaposition, but it kinda works. Acting from the girls was meh, but James…

Cool action scenes and lots of laughter in movie theatre … but dialogue seemed a bit forced and often made scenes … well … cringe. The movie should’ve ended by the end of the second act, but ran for way past that point … and became extremely exhausting.
